ls
Inside a folder you can list all the files that the folder contains using the ls command:

Bash
ls
If you add a folder name or path, it will print that folder contents:

Bash
ls /bin
Highly Useful ls Flags for Everyday Use
When navigating directories, the plain ls command can be a bit minimal. Adding these flags will significantly improve your terminal visibility:

ls -l (Long Listing): Displays detailed information about files, including file permissions, number of links, owner, group, file size, and the last modified date/time.

ls -a (All Files): Reveals hidden files. In Unix-like systems, any file or folder starting with a dot (., such as .bashrc or .git) is hidden by default.

ls -lh (Human-Readable Sizes): When combined with -l, this formats file sizes into an easily readable format (e.g., 4K, 25M, 2G) instead of raw bytes.

ls -t (Sort by Time): Sorts the listed files and folders by their last modified time, putting the newest items at the top.